1
00:00:00.033 --> 00:00:03.466
Welcome to Building Agentic RAG
with LlamaIndex.

2
00:00:03.733 --> 00:00:05.100
I'm joined by Jerry Liu,

3
00:00:05.100 --> 00:00:08.933
who is co-founder and CEO at LlamaIndex
and the instructor for this course.

4
00:00:09.400 --> 00:00:11.866
Thanks, Andrew.
I'm super excited to be here with you.

5
00:00:11.866 --> 00:00:14.966
In this course, you learn about
a agentic RAG, a framework

6
00:00:14.966 --> 00:00:18.100
to help you build research agents
capable of events

7
00:00:18.100 --> 00:00:21.466
to use reasoning and decision
making over your data.

8
00:00:22.100 --> 00:00:24.766
For example,
one of you have a set of research papers

9
00:00:24.766 --> 00:00:28.200
on some topic and you want to pull out
the parts relevant to a question

10
00:00:28.300 --> 00:00:31.300
you want to ask, and you get a synthesis
of what the papers say.

11
00:00:31.733 --> 00:00:35.366
This is a complex requests
that require multiple steps of processing.

12
00:00:35.866 --> 00:00:40.033
Further, various steps of processing,
like maybe identifying a theme

13
00:00:40.033 --> 00:00:43.366
for one paper, but also change
the later steps that are needed,

14
00:00:43.366 --> 00:00:46.900
like retrieving additional information
from other papers about that theme.

15
00:00:47.500 --> 00:00:51.333
In comparison, the standard
RAG pipeline, which is very popular,

16
00:00:51.666 --> 00:00:53.866
is mostly good for simpler questions

17
00:00:53.866 --> 00:00:57.333
over a small set of documents
and works by retrieving some context,

18
00:00:57.700 --> 00:01:01.566
sticking that into the prompt
and then just calling a single time

19
00:01:01.633 --> 00:01:03.100
to get a response.

20
00:01:03.100 --> 00:01:06.966
This course will take the idea of chatting
over your data to the next level,

21
00:01:07.200 --> 00:01:10.633
and show you how to build
an autonomous research agent.

22
00:01:11.166 --> 00:01:13.866
You'll learn a progression
of reasoning ingredients

23
00:01:13.866 --> 00:01:17.433
to building a full agent. First, routing.

24
00:01:17.733 --> 00:01:21.166
We add decision making to route requests
to multiple tools.

25
00:01:21.800 --> 00:01:25.300
Next, tool use.
Where you create an interface for agents,

26
00:01:25.300 --> 00:01:28.966
to selected tool, as well as generate
the right arguments for that tool.

27
00:01:29.500 --> 00:01:32.566
And then finally, multi-step reasoning
with tool use.

28
00:01:32.800 --> 00:01:36.933
We'll use LLM to perform multi-step
reasoning with a range of tools

29
00:01:37.066 --> 00:01:40.066
for retaining memory
throughout that process.

30
00:01:40.133 --> 00:01:43.200
You will learn how to effectively interact
with an agent and use

31
00:01:43.200 --> 00:01:46.200
its capability
for detailed control and oversight.

32
00:01:46.333 --> 00:01:50.100
This will allow you to not only create
a higher level research assistant over

33
00:01:50.100 --> 00:01:54.166
your RAG pipelines, but also give you
more effective ways to guide its actions.

34
00:01:54.633 --> 00:01:58.333
Specifically, you'll learn
how to ensure debug ability of the LLM.

35
00:01:58.700 --> 00:01:59.966
We'll look at how to step through

36
00:01:59.966 --> 00:02:03.233
what your agent is doing
and how to use that to improve your agent.

37
00:02:04.033 --> 00:02:06.700
One additional
very powerful tool is to let the user

38
00:02:06.700 --> 00:02:09.700
optionally inject guidance
at intermediate steps.

39
00:02:09.966 --> 00:02:12.966
For example, if you see us
searching the wrong document,

40
00:02:13.166 --> 00:02:16.633
a little nudge to search
a different document from human input,

41
00:02:16.933 --> 00:02:21.833
much like an experienced manager, that's
you, giving a more junior employee a nudge

42
00:02:21.833 --> 00:02:25.333
to consider a new piece of information
can give much better performance.

43
00:02:25.733 --> 00:02:28.400
Many people have worked to create this
course.

44
00:02:28.400 --> 00:02:31.733
I'd like to thank from LlamaIndex,
Logan Markewich

45
00:02:31.966 --> 00:02:34.666
and Andrei Fajardo. From DeepLearning.AI,

46
00:02:34.666 --> 00:02:38.466
Diala Ezzeddine
also contributed to this course.

47
00:02:38.966 --> 00:02:42.500
In the first lesson, you will build
a router over a single document

48
00:02:42.533 --> 00:02:45.533
that can handle both question
answering as well as summarization.

49
00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:47.233
That sounds great.

50
00:02:47.233 --> 00:02:49.400
Let's go on to the
next video and get started.

